  ('US-RI', 'rrr', 'trust_standard', 'rules_plus_overrides', 'sectioned_only', true, 'R.I. Gen. Laws Title 18 (including § 18-4-27 and Chapter 18-14); R.I. Gen. Laws § 34-4-27', 'No (Rhode Island has its own trust statutes)', 'UNCLEAR — official Rhode Island sources reviewed confirm that a written trust is not invalid merely because the settlor retains a power to revoke, amend, alter, or modify it, but no general default presumption was identified', 'Yes', 'UNCLEAR — official Rhode Island sources reviewed establish that the trust must be created by a written instrument, but no general standalone signature rule was identified from the statutes reviewed', 'Not required for general trust validity in the official Rhode Island sources reviewed; acknowledgment may be required for recordable real property instruments and for a recorded affidavit or memorandum of trust in real-property transactions', 'UNCLEAR — no general witness requirement for trust validity was identified in the official Rhode Island sources reviewed', 'A trust is valid under R.I. Gen. Laws § 18-4-27 if it is otherwise valid and created by a written instrument; real-property trust transactions may use a recorded affidavit or memorandum of trust under R.I. Gen. Laws § 34-4-27', 'R.I. Gen. Laws § 34-4-27 (affidavit or memorandum of trust for real-property transactions)', 'For a recorded affidavit or memorandum of trust in the real-property context: trust name if any; date of trust instrument; name of each settlor; name and address of each current trustee; statement regarding trustee authority to convey, mortgage, lease, grant restrictions, easements, or other interests in real estate, with relevant trust provisions attached; statement whether anything in the trust derogates from those powers', 'Other information contained in an affidavit or memorandum of trust that is relevant to the real-property transaction', 'UNCLEAR — no general statutory prohibition list was identified in the official Rhode Island sou